      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why V-Ending Words Are Rare</h2>

      <p>English spelling conventions almost always add a silent E after V at the end of words. Think LOVE, GIVE, HAVE, MOVE — all end in VE, not V alone. The words that do end in V are mostly borrowed from other languages: Hebrew (TAV, VAV), Bulgarian (LEV), Yiddish (GANEV), or British slang (GUV, LUV).</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Linguistic Insight</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">The <span class="text-white font-medium">"no English word ends in V"</span> rule is one of the oldest spelling conventions in the language. It dates back to Middle English when scribes added -e to distinguish V from U (which shared the same character). Words like REV and GOV are modern abbreviations that break this ancient rule.</p>
      </div>

