<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Hook Plays & Extensions</h2>

<p>Words ending in IN-V create powerful hook opportunities. A hook is when you add letters to an existing word on the board to form a new valid word. If an opponent plays a word, and you can extend it by adding IN-V at the end (or build a parallel word ending in IN-V), you score points for both the new letters and the entire modified word.</p>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
  <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">🪝 Hooking Strategy</p>
  <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Keep an eye on words already on the board that can be extended with an <span class="text-white font-medium">IN-V</span> ending. This lets you build off your opponent's plays for big combination scores, especially near premium squares.</p>
</div>

<p>Defensively, knowing which words end in IN-V helps you avoid leaving hook opportunities for your opponent. Before placing a word, ask yourself: can my opponent add letters to what I just played? If so, consider a different placement that leaves fewer extension points exposed, particularly near triple-word squares.</p>

<p>The IN-V ending pattern also helps with rack management. When you recognise that your remaining tiles could form a word ending in IN-V, you can plan one or two turns ahead — playing supporting tiles first to set up a higher-scoring IN-V word on your next turn. This forward-thinking approach is a hallmark of competitive-level Scrabble.</p>

